text: Hey sentdex, I've never watched any of your videos before this one but a solution to the program letting the neural net stop too often is changing how you handle any non-acceleration action.  Inaction: Release WASD Accelerate: Release SAD, Push W Reverse Accelerate: Release WAD, Push S Turn Left: Release D, Push S Turn Right: Release A, Push D  This would prevent turning from acting as an inaction, and make the inaction a unique movement in that it is the only movement that does not affect movement whatsoever.

author: @BarnacleBrown
text: I think your AI is having a hard time figuring out what its controlling on the screen and how its inputs are affecting its movement.  This is because the cars orientation changes in relation to the camera.  One second turning left for .5 seconds is not the same as another second of doing that in an incredibly variable way because of the angle and position of the car in relation to the background movement of the screen.  Of course the computer could figure it out with enough training... but its making it way harder on it to do it that way. author: @TheSam1902
text: 1:43 If you want to reduce the fluctuations you definitely have to decrease the learning rate: the learning rate is a scalar that multiplies the vector during gradient descent, the higher it is the larger it steps in the gradient descent will be. But if after following the gradient it's accuracy decreases too badly, then it'll quickly recompute a new vector and follow this new one, resulting in a much better accuracy, hence fluctuations.

author: @jonathanmay256
text: Your learning rate is how far the error minimization algorithm "steps" on each iteration of improvement algorithm. It makes sense for a high learning rate to produce an uneven error curve. For each iteration in your improvement algorithm (gradient descent, whatever you're using), your learning parameters will "jump" a large amount in the direction of error minimization. They can overshoot the ideal location for your next iteration (if that makes sense). On your next iteration, the calculated direction for them to jump will be back towards the point of your last iteration, and so forth and so forth.

author: @Worulz
text: the spikes are due to your sample size. For example if you are training through data that it hasn't seen it may have a low prediction rate. and vis-versa. This is what causes fluctuations in accuracy. The large your sample size means, on average your data is very similar to the data you've provided it previously.  Also tensorflow tends to allocate all memory to the network. If it doesn't need to use everything you can also restrict memory usage with a function.

author: @KarfontaAlec
text: A large learning rate will always mean large oscillations in your error because your making large updates to your weights. Though the level of thrashing I am seeing in the charts could just be complexity of the environment. Still you almost always want to have a decaying learning rate. It's going to dramatically speed up the convergence time. If you're using the common ADAM optimizer it is already decaying the learning rate and also adjusting it per parameter to maintain momentum from previous updates.

author: @abcdefgh1279
text: Hey, I am thinking of a few reasons why your AI gets stuck at random points in the game: 1. Too many/wrong edges are being recognized as "the road" 2. Is the whole pathfinding algorithm is based only on the visual recognition and not the other conditions, like if the car is turned 90 degrees in the viewport? (that may change a lot in the camera movement and further path recognition if the AI decides to move at all) Maybe you could try to split the AI, and have multiple independent or nested "cells", or something. One cell would recognize the road in front of the car, second one could calculate the center of "our" lane thus predicting where we want to go. author: @windmill1965
text: I have the impression that the car is overreacting.  When you create training data, you respond to an image. Your response is delayed (human delay) so the keys are logged some time after the image you are responding to. However, this image you responded to is not being used during the creation of the model. The image which is used is the image when the keys are used. It could be that the training data is better if the keys are linked to an image of e.g. 0.2 seconds earlier. A second item could be related to how strong we steer. In real life we tend to steer more in case of low speed and steer less during high speed. I mean the angle of the steering wheel. The model does not seem to be aware of its actual speed. So if it is driving at higher speed than when it was trained it will rotate the steering wheel too far and thus overreact.
